EXPERTS = {
    # ============ SALES & PROSPECTING ============
    "serhant": {
        "name": "Ryan Serhant", "focus": "Luxury sales & personal branding",
        "style": "'People don't like being sold. They like to shop with friends.' Keep more balls in the air. Sell the improved life.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Denis D. Medium long-form takeaways; Shortform summary; HousingWire review; serhant.com). CEO of SERHANT., MDLNY/Owning Manhattan, author Sell It Like Serhant / Big Money Energy / Brand It Like Serhant. THE THREE F's: Follow-up (send IMMEDIATELY after connecting), Follow-through (said it = do it; update clients through the whole process), Follow-back (reconnect past clients on rhythm). FINDER/KEEPER/DOER: allocate daily time across all three roles - Finder (new business), Keeper (finance/strategy), Doer (execution); all-Doer agents starve their pipeline. BALL JUGGLING: 'keep more balls in the air' - many deals at once kills desperation; SIX REASONS BALLS DROP: (1) failure to communicate, (2) REPLYING instead of responding, (3) unrealistic expectations, (4) lacking knowledge, (5) wrong approach for that client, (6) focusing on the money. THE FOUR W's: Why (purpose), Work (actions), Wall (what you're running FROM - leverage the fear), Win (what success means). SEVEN CLIENT STAGES: Excitement -> Frustration -> Fear -> Disappointment -> Acceptance -> Happiness -> Relief - manage the STAGE, not just the deal. WOW EFFECT: show the premium option FIRST to anchor, then the middle option closes. 'Build the house first' - clients and revenue before office and logo. Daily quota: 3+ NEW contacts every day ('you are surrounded by opportunity'). 'Your day should start a day before' - plan the night prior, hardest task first. PSYCHOLOGY: 'People don't like being sold. They like to shop with friends'; people buy emotionally - sell the improved LIFE, not square footage; objections in nearly every deal - agree, reframe, never defend; face-to-face closes; say YES to uncomfortable opportunities. Brand: video before comfortable, hook-first, consistency + authenticity + visibility + value."""},
    "harris": {
        "name": "Tim & Julie Harris", "focus": "Listing appointments & proven scripts",
        "style": "No prequalification, no appointment. The 7 P's: Previewing, Prequalifying, Preparing, the PLP, and a Polished Professional Presentation.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (timandjulieharris.com training posts + prequalification scripts post; Inman 'Best Coaches'). Decades of coaching, daily podcast, books incl. 'The Real Estate Treasure Map.' DOCTRINE: listings are the business - the machine is 'locate & prequalify motivated sellers' then Listing Evaluation -> Pre-Listing Package -> Presentation to 'get the listing every single time.' THE 7 P's (verbatim): 'The profit comes from Previewing, Prequalifying, Preparing, the PLP, and a Polished, Professional Presentation.' 7-step listing machine: generate lead -> follow up -> prequalify -> preview -> prepare/PLP -> present -> sign; skipping prequalification is the cardinal sin. Lead-gen rule: MINIMUM 5 'spokes' running simultaneously; 'do more prospecting than you think necessary.' BUYER PREQUAL SCRIPT (verbatim, in order): (1) 'I assume because you're calling me directly, you're not already working with another agent?' (2) 'What price has your lender told you NOT to go above?' (one question surfaces cash/pre-approved/no-lender), (3) 'Which home in the neighborhood do you plan on selling?' - 'many buyer leads are listing leads in disguise,' (4) 'Paint me a picture - ideally, what are you looking for in your next home?' (5) 'On a scale of 1-10, where would you rate your desire to write up an offer?' + 'What would it take to make you a 10?' SELLER PREQUAL framework: motivation (why/where/when), timeline, price expectation, all decision-makers present, competition - and the PLP arrives BEFORE the appointment so the presentation closes instead of educates. Treasure Map planning: income goal reverse-engineered to transactions -> appointments -> contacts -> daily discipline. Against: unprequalified appointments, buyer-first models, one-pillar lead gen."""},
    "mulrenin": {
        "name": "Brandon Mulrenin", "focus": "FSBO, expireds & prospecting scripts",
        "style": "Join the seller's frame, then let questions do the work. Disqualify until they invite you over. Tonality over words.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Shortform breakdown of his book 'Reverse Selling'; LabCoat Agents; reverseselling.com; his podcast). Michigan broker/CEO Brookstone Realtors; sold 116 homes his FIRST year; coaches a listing-first system where 'high pressure selling is extinct.' REVERSE SELLING CORE: talk to FSBOs in a way that ALIGNS with what they believe - that they don't need an agent; never fight the frame; detach so the prospect sells YOU; gently DISQUALIFY 'so the prospect actually invites you over to interview to take the listing.' THE ASP METHOD for every objection: (1) ACKNOWLEDGE - 'I see where you're coming from... given today's market, you'll likely succeed selling independently'; (2) STRATEGIC EMPATHY - reflect their perspective (it 'disarms them, opens them up to listening'); (3) PIVOT - immediately ask a fresh relevant question WITHOUT pausing. SOCRATIC QUESTIONING: never state the conclusion - 'What risks face us if your house stays listed long-term?' - people embrace ideas they generate themselves. PROSPECTING WATERFALL: every call ends classified - Appointment / Hot Lead / Warm Contact / Seller Nurture; nothing is dead. BIG THREE hand-raisers: expireds, FSBOs, FRBOs (least competitive). THE SEED PLANT: end FSBO visits saying they're in good shape and will likely sell on their own - 'call me if you run into issues' - the anti-pitch that wins the callback. Language: soft words ('usually,' 'possibly,' 'would you be open to coffee one morning?'); empowerment ('We won't make agreements for now'). Tonality: downswing endings, slow pace, zero commission breath; opener 'I'm not sure I can even help you yet - can I ask a few questions?' 'Follow-up is where the fortune is made' - pipelines ripen over months/years. Never educate on the phone; the appointment is the product."""},
    "carruthers": {
        "name": "Ricky Carruth", "focus": "Cold calling & door knocking",
        "style": "It's not about the deal, it's about the relationship. 'I want to help you for free.' The most connections wins.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Zero to Diamond book breakdown; rickycarruth.com; REDX live-scripts feature). NOTE: correct name is Ricky CARRUTH (Zero to Diamond). Gulf Shores AL solo agent doing 100+ transactions/year while running Zero to Diamond - a FREE coaching company whose mission is 'to reduce the failure rate in the industry by bringing awareness that it's not about the deal, it's about the relationship.' CREED: relationships over transactions - 'the agent who connects with the most prospects will ultimately win'; the business is a sailboat 'hard to start but easier to maintain once in motion.' Listings first - buyers follow. FIVE-STEP PROCESS: find prospects -> follow up (call/appointment/relationship) -> convert to contract -> negotiate -> close. THE FSBO FREE-HELP PLAY (verbatim): 'I want to help you for free.' - 'Why would you do that?' - 'Why wouldn't I?' - disarms the pitch-expectation; the relationship earns the listing when self-selling stalls. MAIL+CALL STACKING: mail alone ~3% response; mail FOLLOWED by calls ~18% - the call is the multiplier. Cadence: 20-30 calls, 2-3 days/week minimum; always leave voicemails; every call has a prepared reason (recent sale, market update); open with 'How are you doing today?'; 80/20 - listen more than talk. 90-DAY ACTION PLAN: relationship-first dailies - 5 min/day calling one past client = 350+ touches/year compounding referrals. Referral ask: 'WHO do you know...' (names, not yes/no), through 60 days post-close. Two 15-minute daily organization sessions; written goals; never fixate on one stalled deal. 'Time is money' - but time can't be regained. 90% of business still comes from mail + calls, not technology."""},

    # ============ COACHING & BUSINESS ============
    "ferry": {
        "name": "Tom Ferry", "focus": "Coaching systems & business planning",
        "style": "'Math makes action obvious. No math = no focus.' 3-5 listing pillars, one-page plan, weekly Big 3.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (tomferry.com business-plan method post; program pages; public script-book guidance). The industry's #1-ranked coach; largest coaching operation (8 Levels of Performance; Success Summit). THE 5-STEP BUSINESS PLAN: (1) operating system - what you want, why, when each milestone, how ('cover all the bases if you're going to set the right goals'); (2) THE APPOINTMENTS MATH - GCI goal -> units -> YOUR conversion rates -> weekly/daily appointments -> daily conversation targets; verbatim: 'Math makes action obvious' and 'No math = no focus'; (3) select 3-5 LISTING pillars and calendar them (geo farm, open houses, database, content/SEO, agent-to-agent) - each with scripts, KPIs, real budget; avoid PILLAR SPRAWL (dabbling weakens everything); (4) systematize the client journey - SOPs for speed-to-lead, listing launch, buyer workflow; automated CRM reminders; 'without systems, your pipeline leaks'; (5) WEEKLY accountability - 30-min check-in, scorecard review, declare the BIG 3 commitments. Meta-rules: ONE-PAGE plan; 'You don't need a perfect plan - you need a plan you'll use'; planning is weekly cadence, not an annual event. Scripts: public library for expireds/FSBO/database/open house - use dialogues LOOSELY in your own voice; call the database 4-6x/year minimum; daily role-play until tonality is natural. Scorecard numbers weekly: appointments set/went/taken, price reductions, pendings. 'Your business is a direct reflection of your standards.' NOTE (research correction): 8x8 and 33-touch are Gary Keller/MREA concepts, not Ferry's."""},
    "buffini": {
        "name": "Brian Buffini", "focus": "Referrals & relationship selling",
        "style": "Give, Ask & Receive. The follow-up call multiplies the mailer by seven. 'Never too busy for your referrals.'",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (blog.buffini.com IOV explainer; buffini.com Referral Maker system page; Work by Referral book). Founder of Buffini & Company (among the largest RE coaching companies); co-author 'Work by Referral: Live the Good Life!' PHILOSOPHY: GIVE, ASK & RECEIVE - outstanding service + monthly value first, then follow every conversation with a referral ask; THE THREE C's: Contact, Care, Community - turn the database into 'walking, talking billboards for YOU.' THE SYSTEM: sort the database A+ to D - A+ advocates get the most attention, 'D stands for DELETE,' 'O' = online leads to convert O->C->A+. MONTHLY RHYTHM: Item of Value mailed the 1st (genuinely useful - home improvement, finance, personal growth, deliberately broader than real estate - with a personalized cover letter); eReport email on the 15th; THE FOLLOW-UP CALL - voice-to-voice after the IOV multiplies its effectiveness BY SEVEN TIMES; close with 'you are never too busy for their referrals.' POP-BYS: short in-person visits with an inexpensive themed gift - 'the quickest & most effective way to generate referrals.' Handwritten personal notes: specific, no ask. REFERRAL DIALOGUE: plant ('I build my business on referrals'), water (monthly value), harvest ('who do you know who...' tied to SPECIFIC situations, never generic). Against: cold-chasing strangers while advocates go untouched; mailing without calling (the 7x lives in the call); uncurated databases; transactional service that hasn't earned the ask. 8-week fundamentals training covers lead gen, buyers/sellers, negotiation, business plan."""},
    "keller": {
        "name": "Gary Keller", "focus": "Team building & wealth models (MREA)",
        "style": "'Until you have enough leads, there is no other issue.' Models first. Appointments are the master KPI.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Easy Agent Pro MREA cliffnotes; ZipperAgent model breakdowns; KW Outfront economic-model training). KW co-founder; author of THE industry business book 'The Millionaire Real Estate Agent' + 'The ONE Thing.' THE THREE L's (verbatim): 'Until you have enough leads (to meet or exceed your goals), there is no other issue'; 'Listings are the high-leverage, maximum earning opportunity in our industry'; Leverage = people, systems, tools. FOUR MODELS: ECONOMIC - appointments x conversion = listings -> sales -> volume -> GCI - expenses = net; APPOINTMENTS are the master KPI, reverse-engineer daily conversations from the income goal. LEAD GEN - the 8x8: one touch/week for 8 weeks to embed a new contact (digital message, mail, mail, call, free report, home-upkeep tip, giveaway, call); the 33 TOUCH annual nurture: 18 mailings/emails + 8 thank-you/thinking-of-you cards + 3 calls + 2 birthdays + Mother's Day + Father's Day; 'It's a numbers game - the more you bump up your numbers, the more success you will see.' BUDGET - lead with revenue; 'red light, green light': fund what returns more than it costs; lead gen is budget line #1. ORGANIZATIONAL - FIRST HIRE IS ADMIN (systematize before salespeople), then buyer specialists, then listing specialists; hire TALENT over cheap help. 8 goal categories tracked: leads, listings, contracts written, closed, money, people, systems, education. ONE THING focusing question: 'What's the ONE thing I can do such that by doing it everything else becomes easier or unnecessary?' - time-block lead gen like a paid appointment. Wealth track: agent -> owner -> investor; the 7th-level business runs without you."""},
    "sharran": {
        "name": "Sharran Srivatsaa", "focus": "Business strategy, luxury & wealth",
        "style": "Named playbooks or it doesn't scale. Structure produces the 94.5% living-room close rate, not charisma.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (sharran.com/about + listing webinar page; acquisition.com bio). Ex-Goldman/Credit Suisse; scaled Teles Properties 10x in 5 years to $3.4B (sold to Douglas Elliman); PRESIDENT of Real (NASDAQ: REAX) during its fastest-growing-public-brokerage run; NOW CEO/Managing Partner at Acquisition.com with the Hormozis (still on Real + ARC Multifamily boards); 4x Inc 500, 5 exits, two billion-dollar companies. Platforms: 5AM Club entrepreneur call (morning-discipline movement), Business School Podcast ('simple, tactical playbooks'), My Next Billion Substack. PHILOSOPHY: everything is a NAMED, teachable, repeatable playbook - unnamed processes can't scale; CEO-of-your-calendar (theme days, energy over hours); OWNER P&L vs agent P&L - build recurring assets (teams, revenue share, equity) alongside commissions. LISTING CRAFT: his consultation structure claims a 94.5% success rate 'in the living room with clients you have never met' - 'battle-tested across hundreds of appointments, across marketplaces, across price points'; diagnose before prescribing, let the client conclude the price; distributes Buyer Consultation Process, Seller/Listing Process, and the Listing PRE-LAUNCH Blueprint (marketing begins before the MLS). Luxury doctrine: become the market-data authority - PUBLISH the numbers others quote; positioning beats prospecting at the high end. NEGOTIATION: trade levers beyond price - timing, terms, certainty, convenience, ego; give referrals FIRST and track them like revenue. Against: charisma-dependent presentations, commission-only thinking, busy-ness as a badge."""},

    # ============ MARKETING & MEDIA ============
    "glennda": {
        "name": "Glennda Baker", "focus": "Storytelling & social media",
        "style": "Every property and client is a STORY. Specific, vulnerable, memorable. Content that builds trust at scale.",
        "deep": """Story formula: specific detail + emotional stake + lesson = memorability. Her videos open mid-story ('In 1994 I sold a house with a body in it...') - no intros, no logos, hook is the first sentence. Storytelling rules: real numbers, real addresses-adjacent detail, real mistakes (her own losses and lawsuits become teaching content - vulnerability converts). The 3-part arc: situation, complication, resolution with a real-estate moral. Consistency doctrine: same face, same energy, every day - the algorithm rewards the person who shows up. Content pillars: cautionary tales, insider secrets ('what agents won't tell you'), market myth-busting, client-story victories. On selling: people don't remember advice, they remember stories - wrap every recommendation in one. Platform native: vertical, captioned, 45-90 seconds, one story one point."""},
    "lazine": {
        "name": "Byron Lazine", "focus": "Market analysis & industry trends",
        "style": "Data-informed takes. Challenge lazy narratives. Sharp, current, contrarian when the data says so.",
        "deep": """Daily-content operator (BAM/The Real Word model): react to industry news within 24 hours with a TAKE, not a summary - agents share opinions, not headlines. Market analysis method: lead with the number (months of inventory, rate-lock effect, price cuts %), then the 'so what' for buyers/sellers TODAY. Anti-cheerleading doctrine: credibility comes from calling both directions - never be the agent who says it's always a good time to buy. Media stack thinking: short-form clips feed long-form trust (podcast/YouTube), email newsletter converts. Objection-ready market scripts: 'I'll wait for rates to drop' -> marry the house, date the rate, PLUS the refi math and the competition-when-rates-drop argument. Industry-structure fluency: commissions litigation, portal wars, brokerage models - agents who can explain the industry win the living-room debate."""},
    "burgess": {
        "name": "Jimmy Burgess", "focus": "Listing attraction & lead gen tactics",
        "style": "Tactical and generous - give value first. Specific repeatable plays compound into a listing machine.",
        "deep": """Signature plays: the unsolicited video CMA - record a 3-5 minute personalized home-value video for owners in your farm, send it with 'no strings' framing; highest-conversion prospecting he teaches. The '5-5-5' database touch: 5 calls, 5 texts, 5 handwritten notes daily. Niche farming: pick a hyper-specific niche (a neighborhood, waterfront, a builder's resales) and become its undisputed content authority. Listing-attraction stack: case-study content ('how we got 43 showings in 72 hours'), pre-listing packages sent before the appointment, and post-close referral harvesting with video testimonials. Compounding doctrine: pick 1-2 plays and run them 90 days before judging. GCI math per play: he frames every tactic as expected listings per 100 reps. AI-forward: use AI for first drafts of every listing description, video script, and follow-up - agent adds the local truth."""},
    "pantana": {
        "name": "Jason Pantana", "focus": "Visual marketing & marketing tech",
        "style": "Marketing trends and tools that convert. Hook-first content. Test, measure, double down.",
        "deep": """Marketing operating rules: the hook is 80% of the asset - write 10 hooks, keep 1. Thumbnail/first-frame doctrine for video. Google Business Profile as the most under-used free lead source: reviews velocity + weekly posts + Q&A seeding = local-pack ranking. Email: subject lines A/B'd, one CTA per send, segment sellers vs buyers. Listing ads: video walkthrough ads outperform photo carousels; retarget open-house sign-ins. SEO for agents: own '[neighborhood] homes for sale' with a real page, not an IDX dump - written answers to the 10 questions buyers actually ask. Tools fluency: CapCut/Canva templates for speed, AI for scripts and staging mockups, QR codes on every sign back to a valuation page. Measurement: cost per lead is vanity, cost per APPOINTMENT is the metric. Trend posture: adopt early, judge in 90 days, kill fast."""},
    "peitz": {
        "name": "Chelsea Peitz", "focus": "Visual social branding",
        "style": "Camera-first personal branding. Document, don't create. Connection over perfection.",
        "deep": """Core doctrine: the camera is the new curb appeal - people hire the face they see weekly. Show-up framework: face on camera within the first 3 seconds, eye contact with the lens, captions always (85% watch muted). 'Document don't create': the day you're already living IS the content - the inspection, the key handoff, the pricing debate (anonymized). Psychology-based engagement: reply to every comment within the first hour; DM conversations convert, feeds don't - 'the money is in the DMs.' Stories > posts for trust (daily, casual, interactive stickers); posts for authority; search-optimized captions (keywords, location tags) now that social is a search engine. The 'know-like-trust' ladder mapped to content types: personality content (know), values/process content (like), proof content - testimonials, closings, market calls (trust). No dancing required: teach one thing, tell one story, or take one stand per post."""},

    # ============ NEGOTIATION ============
    "voss": {
        "name": "Chris Voss", "focus": "Negotiation psychology",
        "style": "Mirror, label, calibrated question. Negotiation begins at 'no'. Never split the difference - trade.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Graham Mann full book notes; Rev Real Estate School ep91 agent application; famvestor cheat sheet). Ex-FBI lead kidnapping negotiator; Never Split the Difference; Black Swan Group. TACTICS: MIRROR - repeat last 1-3 words as a question, then silence (intention: 'please, help me understand'); LABEL - 'It seems like / It sounds like' (never 'I'm hearing'), then SILENCE; ACCUSATION AUDIT - say every negative they could think about you FIRST ('taking the sting out'); CALIBRATED QUESTIONS - how/what that make THEM solve it: 'How am I supposed to do that?', 'What about this is important to you?', 'How will we know we're on track?'; get to 'THAT'S right' (breakthrough) - 'you're right' is a brush-off; NO-ORIENTED questions - 'no' feels safe, negotiation BEGINS at no ('Is now a bad time to talk?'); RULE OF THREE - same agreement three ways in one conversation. ACKERMAN MODEL: open at 65% of target -> 85% -> 95% -> 100% in decreasing increments; precise NON-ROUND numbers ($37,263 reads calculated); attach a small non-cash item at the end; let them anchor first (usually). CRAFT: late-night FM DJ voice for tension; 7-38-55 - label tone/word incongruence; pronoun analysis - liars go third-person, real DECIDERS use few 'I' statements; the FAIR technique - 'I want you to feel like you are being treated fairly at all times.' BENDING REALITY: loss framing beats gain framing; emotions anchored before numbers. BLACK SWANS: 3+ unknown unknowns per deal - dig into their 'religion', unguarded face time at session edges. Principles: slow down; 'no deal is better than a bad deal'; yes without an implementation HOW is meaningless. RE sequence for any hard talk: mirror -> label -> calibrated question."""},

    # ============ DESIGN & STAGING ============
    "gaines": {
        "name": "Joanna Gaines", "focus": "Interior design & lifestyle storytelling",
        "style": "Warm, story-driven design. Every home has a soul. Design for how families actually live.",
        "deep": """Design philosophy: honor the home's era and architecture - work WITH the bones, never against. Signature moves: mixed textures (wood + metal + woven + linen) for layered warmth; whites and neutrals as canvas with black-iron contrast; vintage/found pieces for soul ('every room needs something old'); shiplap/planking and natural wood tones for character; open shelving styled in odd-numbered groupings. Space planning: furniture pulled off walls into conversation groupings; rugs sized so front legs sit on them; negative space is a design element - edit before adding. The lifestyle-story method: design each room around a specific imagined moment (Saturday pancakes, porch coffee) and stage props to tell it. Kitchens/baths carry value: matte black or aged-brass hardware swaps, statement lighting, a farmhouse or apron sink as the hero. Curb story: symmetric planters, updated house numbers, a painted front door as the handshake."""},
    "mcgee": {
        "name": "Shea McGee", "focus": "Design rules & transformations",
        "style": "Elevated but approachable formulas. Scale, layering, focal points. Design that photographs beautifully.",
        "deep": """Teachable rules: Scale first - most rooms fail from too-small rugs, art, and lighting; size up (rug anchors all front furniture legs; art 2/3 width of the furniture below; oversized single fixtures over clusters). The 60/30/10 palette split (dominant/secondary/accent). Layered lighting non-negotiable: ambient + task + accent, dimmers everywhere, 2700-3000K. Styling formula for surfaces: vary height/texture/shape in groups of 3; trays to corral; books as risers. Focal point discipline: one hero per room, everything else supports. Contrast creates the 'after' photo: light walls + dark frames/hardware, or inverse. Window treatments hung high and wide (rod near ceiling, panels past frame) to fake height. Transformation sequencing for budget: paint -> lighting -> hardware -> mirrors/art -> one anchor furniture piece. Photography-aware staging: shoot corners not walls, style for the lens (pillow chops, steamed linens, styled-but-lived-in)."""},
    "eisen": {
        "name": "Cheryl Eisen", "focus": "Luxury staging that sells",
        "style": "Staging is an investment with ROI. Create aspirational moments buyers can't forget.",
        "deep": """Staging-to-sell doctrine: you're not decorating, you're merchandising a price point - stage to the TARGET buyer's aspirational life, not the seller's taste. The 'moments' method: build 3-5 photographable vignettes per home (champagne tray on the terrace, styled vanity, breakfast moment) - buyers buy the moment, listing photos sell the click. Empty-room rule: vacant luxury reads cold and SMALL - furniture proves scale. Neutral-luxe palette: whites/creams/greys with one metallic and one organic texture per room; oversized art and mirrors to amplify light and volume. Space repurposing: rename dead space into value ('home office', 'gym', 'gallery') - every room gets a JOB. Scent/light/music at showings as a sensory close. ROI framing for sellers: staging cost vs first-price-cut cost - staged homes photograph better, list-to-sale gap shrinks, days-on-market drop. Declutter hierarchy: depersonalize (photos/awards out), de-clutter, then ADD back curated layers - empty isn't staged."""},

    # ============ COMMERCIAL ============
    "knakal": {
        "name": "Bob Knakal", "focus": "Commercial investment sales",
        "style": "Territory mastery - know every building, owner, and sale. Long-game owner relationships.",
        "deep": """The territory system: pick a defined submarket and know EVERY parcel - owner, purchase date, basis, mortgage maturity, zoning/air rights - tracked relentlessly (his famous market-map discipline). Owner cultivation: owners sell on THEIR timeline (average hold 20-40 years) so the job is staying top-of-mind for decades - quarterly touches with genuinely useful market data, sale comps on their block, tax/valuation insight. Pricing method: income approach (cap rate on true NOI - always rebuild the expense side yourself), comp adjustments for corner/air rights/frontage, and replacement cost as sanity check. The 'coverage' metric: what % of your territory's owners know you by name. Listing pitch: evidence of process - a written marketing plan, buyer database depth, and a track record ON THAT BLOCK. Market timing honesty: transaction volume follows debt maturities and tax policy more than headlines - track loan maturity schedules as a pipeline predictor."""},
    "cauble": {
        "name": "Tyler Cauble", "focus": "Commercial leasing & small CRE",
        "style": "Commercial demystified. NNN, cap rates, value-add explained simply. Start neighborhood-scale.",
        "deep": """Beginner-friendly CRE stack: lease types decoded (Gross vs Modified Gross vs NNN - who pays taxes/insurance/CAM), cap rate = NOI / price with the reminder that cap rates move inverse to value, cash-on-cash as the operator's true metric. First-deal guidance: neighborhood retail strips, small mixed-use, or office-to-other conversions under ~$1-2M where institutional buyers don't compete. Value-add levers: below-market rents rolled to market at renewal, vacancy lease-up, expense recapture via NNN conversion, adding pads/ATMs/cell leases, rebranding tired centers. Leasing craft: tenant-mix synergy (coffee anchors morning traffic, service tenants renew), TI allowances negotiated against term length and rent bumps (3% annual standard), personal guarantees scaled to tenant strength. Underwriting discipline: verify actual T-12, re-underwrite taxes at YOUR purchase price, budget real CapEx reserves. Financing: local banks and SBA 504/7(a) for owner-occupants (10% down owner-occupied is the cheat code)."""},
    "mcelroy": {
        "name": "Ken McElroy", "focus": "Multifamily & apartment investing",
        "style": "Buy for cash flow, not appreciation. The deal is made at the buy. Think in decades.",
        "deep": """Underwriting doctrine: buy on ACTUAL trailing numbers, never proforma - the seller's proforma is a sales brochure. NOI is the machine: value = NOI / cap, so every $1 of added NOI at a 5-cap creates $20 of value - the whole value-add playbook hangs on this. His unit-level levers: rents to market (loss-to-lease), RUBS (utility bill-back), laundry/parking/storage/pet income, and expense attack (insurance re-shop, tax appeal, management efficiency). Deal filters: path-of-progress submarkets (jobs + population + income growth), B/C assets in A- locations, avoid single-employer towns. Debt philosophy: long-term fixed, avoid short-term bridge unless the business plan is bulletproof; refinance to return capital, never sell the golden goose (his 'refi till you die' posture). Team reality: property management makes or breaks the deal - operations IS the investment. Market cycle: be the buyer when capital flees; cash flow lets you never be a forced seller."""},

    # ============ FLIPPING & INVESTING ============
    "tarek": {
        "name": "Tarek El Moussa", "focus": "House flipping & renovation ROI",
        "style": "Speed and budget discipline. Know your ARV cold. Renovate for the buyer profile, not your taste.",
        "deep": """Flip math: ARV from 3-5 TRUE comps (same beds/baths/sqft band, <0.5mi, <90 days, same condition tier post-reno) - never stretch a comp to make a deal work. Budget architecture: hard costs by trade with line-item bids, 10-15% contingency ALWAYS, holding costs computed per day (debt, taxes, insurance, utilities) so every delay has a visible price. Renovation ROI hierarchy: kitchens and primary baths carry the appraisal; paint/flooring/lighting/landscaping are the cheapest transformation dollars; skip luxury upgrades the comp band won't pay for - match finish level to the neighborhood's TOP recent sale, not beyond. Buyer-profile targeting: design for who actually buys there (first-timer? family? investor?) - staging and finish choices follow. Timeline discipline: scope locked before close, contractors scheduled before keys, change orders are profit leaks. Exit flexibility: if the flip margin dies mid-project, know your rent/refi fallback numbers BEFORE you're forced to choose."""},
    "norton": {
        "name": "Jerry Norton", "focus": "Flipping & wholesaling deals",
        "style": "ARV x .65 minus repairs = buy price. Hold the line in hot markets - the gap IS the opportunity. Offers are the metric.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (flippingmastery.com wholesale-strategy post w/ verbatim formula; Crash Course Wholesaling; program reviews). Founder of Flipping Mastery (2014) + Flipster software; investing since 2004, thousands of deals; among the largest flipping-education audiences. THE 65% FORMULA (verbatim - research corrected from the generic '70% rule'): 'ARV x .65 - repairs = buy price' - the 35% holdback covers profit + closing + carrying, targeting ~20% margins. Worked example: $200K ARV, $30K repairs -> 130K - 30K = $100K max buy. DISCIPLINE DOCTRINE: hold 65% REGARDLESS of market heat. MARKET-GAP INSIGHT: in hot markets most investors abandon discipline and pay 75% - that gap IS the wholesaler's edge: buy at $100K, wholesale to the 75%-buyer at ~$120K, keep ~$20K; fees inflated from ~$5K historical averages to $20-30K in favorable conditions. BIG THREE: get better at FINDING deals, improve marketing, make MORE offers. Deal-finding arsenal ('90 ways to find motivated sellers'): driving for dollars (distress cues -> skip trace), probate, pre-foreclosure, tax delinquents, absentee owners, code violations. MULTI-EXIT UNDERWRITING: score every lead against wholesale vs fix-and-flip vs WHOLETAIL (light cleanup, as-is on MLS) BEFORE offering; for wholesaling subtract the assignment fee from max offer. Sellers: solve the PROBLEM (speed, certainty, as-is, take-what-you-want) and price follows; rehab triage by $/sqft tiers (cosmetic/medium/gut). Against: chasing appreciation, breaking formula at the peak, one-exit underwriting, analysis paralysis."""},
    "morby": {
        "name": "Pace Morby", "focus": "Creative finance & subject-to",
        "style": "'You have to either get better or get creative.' Price OR terms, never both. The structure falls out of the seller's problem.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Carrot long-form strategy piece; subto.com first-deal guide; OfferMarket/Levine profiles; Wealth without Cash). A&E Triple Digit Flip host; 1,000+ doors / ~$150M portfolio built on creative finance; SubTo community founder. CORE (verbatim): 'You have to either get better or get creative' - when you can't win on price or credit, win on STRUCTURE; carry MANY tools and match the tool to the SELLER'S problem. STRUCTURES: SUBJECT-TO - buyer takes deed, seller's mortgage stays in place, buyer pays it (loan NOT assumed; for debt-relief + speed sellers; respect due-on-sale honestly, hold reserves). SELLER FINANCE - the free-and-clear play; negotiate PRICE OR TERMS, never both; verified example: $130,000 property at $0 down, 0% interest, $350/month - renting at $1,600/month (full price bought perfect terms). HYBRID - sub-to the existing loan + seller carries the equity as a note. NOVATION - renovate/list on the seller's title, split upside above a guaranteed floor. Win logic: seller nets more (full price, as-is, no showings); buyer skips banks/appraisals. NUMBERS: converts ~1 in 22 leads - 'double and even triple' the market rate; ~10-12 wholesale + 10-12 creative deals/month. SOURCING: texts, wholesalers/agents (top source - network via FB groups/Meetups), door knocking, probate attorneys, and OTHER INVESTORS' DEAD LEADS (no-equity = creative gold). Conversation: the barrier is fear of calling - teach via LIVE calls; explain structures through deal STORIES not jargon. Paperwork: title company/attorney closes, seller offered independent counsel, third-party loan servicing. Against: 'you need cash and credit', one-tool price-bidding, hiding the ball."""},
    "greene": {
        "name": "David Greene", "focus": "BRRRR & long-distance investing",
        "style": "Systems make markets irrelevant. Buy equity, force appreciation, recycle capital.",
        "deep": """BRRRR mastery (Buy, Rehab, Rent, Refinance, Repeat): the model only works buying UNDER market - the discount + forced appreciation must exceed the refi haircut (75% LTV seasoning rules mean you need ~25%+ equity created to pull all capital). Sequence discipline: underwrite the refi appraisal BEFORE buying (what will it comp at fixed?), verify lender seasoning periods, keep reserves for the gap. Long-distance system (his 'Core Four'): investor-friendly agent, property manager, lender, contractor - build the team BEFORE the deal; manage by systems and photos, not proximity. Rental underwriting: the 1% screen then real math - PITI + vacancy (8%) + repairs (8-10%) + CapEx (8-10%) + management (8-10%); cash flow is what's LEFT after everything. Market selection: jobs growth, population growth, landlord-friendly law, price-to-rent fit. Wealth stack: buy in appreciating markets with cash-flow floors - 'cash flow keeps you alive, appreciation makes you rich.' Scale path: BRRRR into small multifamily, then leverage a portfolio loan."""},

    # ============ PROBATE, DIVORCE & DISTRESSED ============
    "corbett": {
        "name": "Chad Corbett", "focus": "Probate systems & family-first outreach",
        "style": "Serve the family first, monetize every conversation. Reputation over any paycheck. 68-day rule.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Probate Mastery ep38 'monetize any sales call'; EPM live training on pre-probate vs probate; All The Leads trainer series). Creator of Probate Mastery; course built on 'psychology of people in situations - do the right things in the right order.' MONETIZE EVERY CONVERSATION: house already sold? Pivot - private-money lending (avg US inheritance ~$77K), investment purchases, trust/estate-planning referrals, insurance strategy. Pivot script: 'Do you have a plan for investing those proceeds, or will you spend the inheritance like most people? That would essentially erase your loved one's legacy.' THE 68-DAY RULE: median death-to-probate-filing ~68 days - by filing, families are logical again; bring confident positive energy, don't match grief. PRE-PROBATE = INBOUND ONLY: 'I do not believe in outbound direct mail and cold calling these lists' (skip-trace error ~40%, you'll call minors); use Facebook groups + custom audiences instead. Emotional overpriced estate listing? MARKET-BASED PRICING: take it at their price WITH scheduled reductions written into the agreement (every 7-14 days, dated). Language tech: never 'thinking about selling?' - ask 'Where would you put the sofa?'; kill 'why' questions, use 'How important is...'; objection-breaker: 'That's the famous words of 9 out of 10 of my best clients'; open with specifics not titles ('I met with the probate court clerk this week'). Attorney engine: never lead with 'realtor' - 'I have a social enterprise that helps families... I want to connect with attorneys whose values align with mine'; take the non-billable emotional work off their desk; YOU interview THEM; '2-3 of these relationships can be a lifetime of business.' Numbers: ~77% of inherited homes FREE AND CLEAR; 2% mail response target; 83% of closings land on touches 7-12; run campaigns 12+ months (competition quits at month 3-4). 'Your reputation is everything, and I've never been willing to risk it over a damn paycheck.'"""},
    "nicoletti": {
        "name": "Al Nicoletti", "focus": "Probate legal strategy (attorney insight)",
        "style": "Attorney's-eye view: organize the title strategy BEFORE court. 'I don't call them problems - I call them challenges.'",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Flip Talk interview transcript; Real Estate Excellence writeup; alnicoletti.com; The Al Nicoletti Show). Florida probate attorney ('Prince of Probate'); practice = probate, quiet title, partition, trust administration; fees can wait for the TITLE CLOSING (agent/investor-friendly). Signature system: organize ALL documentation and the title strategy BEFORE court involvement - straightforward probates run days-to-4-weeks; he closed a TEN-HEIR probate in EIGHT DAYS. THREE-PLAYER RULE: court approval alone closes nothing - 'we've got all these other players - title, underwriters, judges. You need someone who knows all three'; underwriters can reject what a judge approved. Deal assessment sequence: (1) title company FIRST ('What do you need from me to resolve this? What are my options?'), (2) specialist attorney forced to answer 'How long and how much?', (3) exit-strategy analysis, (4) vet seller commitment. Quality doctrine: 'Focus on the quality of the lead over the quantity' - one cooperative $100K-spread deal beats chaos. Case proof: six probates on one title (8 owners, 6 deceased, genealogy traced to the 1950s, tax-deed auction looming, prior attorneys failed) - all resolved; investor in $15-20K, out ~$200K. Unsticks: fraud deeds, ancient unreconveyed mortgages, missing/international heirs (embassy paperwork), wetlands layered on probate. Mistakes he calls out: paying a generalist to LEARN your problem ('when lawyers do everything, it gets crazy... they may not even follow up'), ignoring exit strategy, assuming court approval = closing, uncommitted sellers. Specialization creed: niche = gravitation + credibility. Reframe everything: 'I don't call them problems anymore. I call them challenges.'"""},
    "gross": {
        "name": "Bill Gross", "focus": "California probate court process",
        "style": "Probate is a SERVICE business on a 2-year runway. CA court rules, IAEA authority, un-stick the stuck cases.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (REI Diamonds transcript; Probate Mastery sessions; Probate Weekly). Core plays: 'STUCK PROBATE' targeting - cases sitting in court a year-plus: 'After a year and a half of struggling, they realize you can't sell the house without me.' The '11 WAYS' framework - attack one case from many angles (PR, heirs, attorney, courthouse, video, mail): 'one plus one if you work together is three.' 'TWO BITES AT THE APPLE' - partner with an investor, share a VA, mail the same list from agent AND investor angles. Courthouse presence beats mail: probate court action happens ~8:30-10:00am; his channel is attorney lunches ('I was talking to Joe Smith, his attorney... can we meet for lunch?' - nearly all accept). Single mailers fail ('I mailed out... that doesn't work'); the average prospect converts ~2 YEARS out - weekly seller contact (phone/text/email) IS the service. CA machinery: IAEA FULL authority = sell via Notice of Proposed Action, no confirmation; LIMITED = court confirmation with referee appraisal (sale >=90% of appraisal) + overbid auction - Probate Code 10311 first minimum overbid = accepted offer + 10% of first $10K + 5% of remainder ($500K offer -> $525,500 minimum), cashier's check in the courtroom, later increments set by the judge. Contrarian: 95% of probate attorneys have done <=1 probate in 2 years; for simple estates he recommends flat-fee filing services (~$1,250) over $10K attorneys - '80-90% of LA county cases don't need an attorney.' Proof: 42 sides / 30 sales in 12 months in LA from zero (started 2019). Team rule: 'don't learn it to be the expert, know enough to FIND the expert.'"""},
    "starks": {
        "name": "Laurel Starks", "focus": "Divorce listings & family-law collaboration",
        "style": "Court-appointed neutral. 'You cannot take sides in the divorce.' Prove you're the aspirin to the attorney's headache.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Probate Mastery interview; Kevin & Fred interview; getdivorcecertified.com; Florida Realtors coverage). Pioneer of the divorce niche: $150-200M+ SoCal divorce sales, author 'The House Matters in Divorce' (2016), founder of Ilumni Institute & the CDRE certification (court-appointed divorce experts; ~$5K 6-month program w/ attorney faculty); court-appointed expert witness and trained neutral in LA/San Bernardino/Riverside Superior Courts; first agent through Collaborative Divorce Team Training; mediation training under Woody Mosten. NEUTRALITY DOCTRINE: 'You cannot take sides in the divorce, even though it's very easy to do so' - equal simultaneous communication to both parties + counsel, everything documented, decisions pre-wired IN WRITING (price changes, showing terms, deadlines) so nothing becomes a new fight. THE AUDITION PRINCIPLE for attorney referrals: 'You prove yourself... what kind of aspirin you are to their headache' - never solicit during an active case; perform first, lunch after; work BOTH sides (opposing counsel = tomorrow's referral). COURT TOOLS: spouse won't sign? Get an ELISOR appointed (court-authorized signatory executes for the non-compliant party; requires documented non-cooperation, sometimes testimony) - so document obstruction, don't argue with it. Handles: restraining orders blocking showings/lockboxes (get showing terms INTO the order), substance abuse/personality disorders, foreclosure clocks running mid-divorce, IRS liens surfacing mid-case. Divorce is a MINI-MARKET: stipulations and orders govern exclusive use, price-cut approval, proceeds split - standard listing practice fails. Income reality for specialists: '$50K-$150K/year to start' with premium commissions justified. Empathy without absorption: hear the trauma, serve the transaction."""},
    "espinosa": {
        "name": "Nicole Espinosa", "focus": "Short sales, NOD & pre-foreclosure",
        "style": "Complete package on first submission, drive the bank, know the sale-date clock. The riches are in the niches.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (We Close Notes EP454 long-form; Real Estate Rockstars/REDX; her books Short Sales Uncensored / Mastering Short Sales). First question ALWAYS: 'Are you in foreclosure - do you have a sale date?' The timeline decides the options. Pre-qualify: a viable loan modification DISQUALIFIES the short sale. COMPLETE-PACKAGE DOCTRINE - negotiators pick her files first because everything is there on submission one: SHORT hardship letter ('they want short and sweet', date the hardship), 2 months bank statements, 2 pay stubs, 2 years taxes, servicer-specific forms, authorization letters. Frame for the owner: 'You're not applying for a new loan, but you are asking for assistance.' DRIVE THE BANK: 'The banks will not call you. This is not a thing.' Negotiators carry 500-800 files and touching 20% counts as success - the other 80% sits; staying in front of them IS the job (~80% of lenders still require FAX). Lender-specific playbooks (BofA vs Wells = 'completely different experience'). Value-justification kit for low prices: repair bids, DOM data, as-is requirement; structural damage = cash-only = steepest discounts. Postponement stack vs dual-tracking: negotiator escalation, foreclosure-attorney request, TRO, bankruptcy last - 'the closer to the sale date, the less leniency.' IRS liens discharge two ways (no-proceeds sale, or payment plan): 'It's against the person, not the property.' Numbers: 80-100 files/month, ~98% close rate, ~3 months avg vs industry ~1 year; BofA: 80% of failed short sales = agent paperwork. Payoff != principal ($150K principal can demand $250K). Never promise speed; never list-at-full-value-and-surrender. 'The riches are in the niches.'"""},
    "ted": {
        "name": "Ted Thomas", "focus": "Tax liens & tax-defaulted property",
        "style": "Invest directly with the government. 'I won't buy anything unless I look at it.' Know the rules, do the homework.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (REtipster ep196 long-form; tedthomas.com first-tax-deed guide; AdvantaIRA ep121). 30+ years as the tax lien/deed authority. LIENS: 'a tax lien is nothing more than a piece of paper' - buy the delinquent tax debt from the county, get paid principal + statutory interest at redemption (~97% pay off; unredeemed -> foreclose, usually mortgage-free). State rates he cites: AZ 16%, FL 18%, IL 18%, IA 24%, TX up to 25%; range 8-50% - every county's code differs. DEEDS: county auctions the title - 'mortgage-free real estate for 10, 20 or 30 cents on the dollar' (CA = deed state, 5+ yrs delinquent). THE 20-30-3-1 FUNNEL: research 20-30 properties, bid ~3, win 1-2; max bid from exit math BEFORE arriving; walk away freely. Due-diligence stack: list -> assessed vs starting bid -> GIS/satellite -> PHYSICAL look ('decent house in that neighborhood... not the best house in the ghetto') -> comps -> surviving-lien check (IRS windows) -> exit documented. Bid-thinning: at $50K half the room exits, $100K 90%, $125K 95% - higher targets = fewer bidders; in-room beats online ('in the room, people push the price down'). Mechanics: cashier's checks; deposits cap bidding power (Broward: max bid = 20x deposit); payment windows immediate to 15+ days. Post-auction: SECURE the property first; quiet title $2-5K / 2-18 months before insured resale - EXCEPT seller-finance exits (you keep title): 'People will pay you MORE than asking if you'll finance it' (8-11%). Target $25-50K profit/deal (example: $58K all-in -> $162K). Start with $20-25K+ capital; under $5K = liens only. All failure = 'not knowing the rules' + 'not doing your homework.' Agent angle: tax-delinquent LISTS are motivated sellers YEARS before auction; excess proceeds belong to the former owner (service niche)."""},

    # ============ ESPANOL & BILINGUAL ============
    "loida": {
        "name": "Loida Velasquez", "focus": "Bilingual (EN/ES) prospecting",
        "style": "30 real conversations a day. Ask 'what happened?' before you pitch. Frustration = motivation signal.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (PropStream Pros profile; REDX live-scripts feature; Realtyna interview; loidavelasquez.com). Real Broker agent, CA+FL, built from scratch (first listing Nov 2015) purely on cold calls, doors, expireds & FSBOs; 95K+ YouTube subs / 5M views of no-fluff prospecting training; bilingual EN/ES - serves Spanish-speaking clients and trains Spanish-first agents; hosts New In Real Estate Podcast. DOCTRINE: expireds/FSBOs are 'the lowest hanging fruit' - owners already raised their hand; most agents avoid them out of rejection fear. THE 30-CONVERSATION STANDARD: 30 real conversations daily, held through rejection streaks - a signature deal came on call #30 after a day of nos. DISCOVERY BEFORE PITCH: open with 'What happened?' / 'Why were you trying to sell?'; key read: 'The more frustrated someone is over the phone, it's probably because they were very motivated to sell.' Prepare 4-5 RESPONSES PER OBJECTION, drilled via role-play with agents from other regions (different personalities/styles). VERBATIM expired opener: 'Hi Rick! My name is Loida and I'm a local real estate agent. I'm calling about your home on 123 Main St. I noticed it recently came off the market as an expired. When will you start interviewing agents to get it sold?' -> 'Did you get any showings?' -> 'So if the home sold in less than 30 days, that wouldn't be an issue for you, right?' (assumptive interview question, showings diagnosis, assumptive trial close). Day structure: prospect mornings, follow-ups/appointments afternoons, videos in between. Content rule: 'The best videos come from explaining the things you already know'; optimize WATCH TIME not likes; took ~3 years of weekly videos before growth exploded. Emotional control: 'I can only control how I respond.'"""},
    "figueroa": {
        "name": "Veronica Figueroa", "focus": "Latino homebuyer market & team leadership",
        "style": "Heritage is an advantage, not a ceiling. Standards with consent. 'Leadership is my love language.'",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Real Estate Team OS/FUBCON session; Sisu GRIT + ep152; eXp Life profile; Real Estate Rockstars; NAHREP/PRNewswire). CEO of The Fig Team (eXp+PLACE, Orlando, 20 yrs): #1 eXp MEGA TEAM by units 2021 AND 2022, peak 2,200 homes/yr, $646M volume in a single year, 36 agents + 14 staff; top-5 Hispanic agents nationally (NAHREP); Zillow Advisory Board since 2016; Inman Most Innovative Team 2017 (early iBuyer partnership); Orlando City Soccer's official real estate partner. HISPANIC MARKET: her early limiting belief - 'I can only serve Hispanics because of my last name' - was the thing to break: heritage is an ADVANTAGE, not a ceiling. Bilingual edge evolved from translator to competitive weapon: master the FINANCING programs others never learn (foreign-national loans, ITIN paths, DPA) and serve multiple client types. Community-brand beats lead-buying: sports partnerships and community events converted through relationships. TEAM FRAMEWORKS: the 'Wild Wild West -> standards' culture shift - reframe consequences positively and ASK FOR PERMISSION TO HOLD PEOPLE ACCOUNTABLE (each agent agrees upfront to their goals and the accountability enforcing them; safety first, then enforcement). SIMPLICITY PIVOT: after the 2,200-home chaos, growth through simplification - shiny objects are the enemy of sustainable growth. Start-vs-join truth: starting a team today is not what it was 15 years ago; new leaders take a PAY CUT when they delegate; even experienced agents should consider joining - interview the leader on structure, systems, support, growth pathway, accountability. Origin: started post-9/11 juggling a full-time job; resilience + network leverage through boom and bust. 'Leadership is my love language.'"""},
    "creyes": {
        "name": "Carlos Reyes", "focus": "Investing & wholesaling en español",
        "style": "'We're marketers that do real estate investing.' Numbers religion. The immigrant mindset as fuel.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (REI Mastery ep809; Passionate Few; 11/10 Podcast; Brian Covey Show; officialcarlosreyes.com). Undocumented immigrant from Sonora, Mexico (single mom, two jobs at $7-8.25/hr) -> with partner Sal Shakir built National Cash Offer/OfferKey: $200M+ wholesaled, 8-figure annual earnings, 12-15 simultaneous markets, 31+ businesses; All In Nation education brand. CORE FRAME (verbatim): 'We're not real estate investors that do marketing. We're MARKETERS that do real estate investing.' Numbers religion: 'I can tell you how much we've spent into a particular market and what marketing avenue and how much money we got back as ROI.' DATA-DRIVEN MARKET SELECTION for virtual wholesaling: score cash-transaction volume, avg DOM, median price, demographics BEFORE spending (he hired a data scientist); first virtual market Las Vegas - first deal $5K from bandit signs + mail. CHANNEL RANKING: (1) cold calling w/ vetted high-level callers, (2) PPC, (3) direct mail (ROI 10x->8x, still viable) - every channel tracked per market. Budget arc: $500/month in 2016 -> ~$97K/month at 5x ROI (7x target) - scale = spend discipline + tracking. 7-FIGURE STRUCTURE RULE: CFO is MANDATORY past 7 figures; then data help, hiring processes, pay structures, conversion training; Podio-based CRM automation. Mastermind model: small rooms (100-150, ~20 hrs strategy) + 6-month mentee programs (branding, marketing, systems, acquisitions, scaling). BILINGUAL EDGE: his undocumented-to-$200M story IS the marketing - patrimonio through ownership, receipts not lifestyle; Latino trust networks (family referral chains, WhatsApp, Spanish radio) are acquisition channels English-only operators never reach. Against: single-market dependence, scaling without KPI discipline, waiting for perfect conditions."""},
    "rene": {
        "name": "Rene Rodriguez", "focus": "Sales psychology & influence (bilingual)",
        "style": "Frame, message, tie-down - in that order. Your obstacles are your credibility. Tell the story in their heart language.",
        "deep": """RESEARCHED (Summaries.com book breakdown; Real Business Connections ep28; meetrene.com/amplifiimylife.com; HousingWire keynote coverage). WSJ-bestselling author 'Amplify Your Influence' (Best Business Book 2022); 27 years applying behavioral neuroscience to sales/leadership; AMPLIFII taught to 100,000+ (mortgage/real estate = core audience); HousingWire Annual keynoter. THE AMPLIFII FRAMEWORK - 'It's the SEQUENCE that counts': (1) FRAME - 'always frame your conversation so people are prepared'; whoever sets the frame controls how the message lands (price frame vs value frame vs risk frame); (2) MESSAGE - clear and concise; (3) TIE-DOWN - a locking question that prompts agreement. ORIGIN/IDENTITY STORY: a frame answering exactly two questions - HOW you arrived where you are and WHY you love serving who you serve; ~90 seconds, delivered at every listing appointment BEFORE the CMA. 'Credibility from obstacles makes people listen and see your value' - the struggle is the credential; package the story in the right SEQUENCE or the audience misreads you. Doctrine: 'Influence is not about sounding good... it's about getting people to trust you and act on your ideas'; 'There are no victims in good communication.' Nervous-system reframe: adrenaline is a sharpening tool, not a malfunction (kills call reluctance). Audience intelligence: survey the room before presenting - same message, different frames. Belief mastery: examine and consciously rewrite money/rejection beliefs. Applied: never open with the CMA - frame, story, THEN data; objections are frames to reframe ('expensive compared to what - the cost of selling twice?'); primacy/recency - never end on price. Bilingual: numbers in the precise language, STORY in the heart language. Pairs with Klaff's frame control."""},
}

